library(readxl)
library('ggplot2')
dat <- readxl::read_xls('./GSS.xls')
dat <- dat%>% 
  rename(year = 'Gss year for this respondent', happiness = 'General happiness', partyid = 'Political party affiliation', income = 'Total family income', sex = 'Respondents sex', educ = 'Highest year of school completed', age = 'Age of respondent', marital = 'Marital status', id = 'Respondent id number', ballot = 'Ballot used for interview')
dat$educ <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(dat$educ))
dat$age <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(dat$age))
  1. We can see that for all party identifications, the average years of school is from 12 to 14 years of schooling. The political party identification with the greatest average years of school is strong republican. The political party identification with the smallest average years of school is dont know.
dat%>%
  select(partyid, educ)%>%
  filter(educ<21)%>%
  group_by(partyid)%>%
  summarise(educ_mean = mean(educ), .groups='drop')

df <- dat%>%
  group_by(partyid)%>%
  filter(educ<21)%>%
  mutate(partyMedian = median(educ))%>%
  filter(educ > partyMedian)%>%
  select(-partyMedian)%>%
  ungroup()

  1. From the plot, we can see that married has the most happy respondents. The group with the least amount of happy people are those who did not answer. However, if we disregard the no answer category, the group with the least amount of happy people are those who are separated. For this I used the variables happiness and marital.
dat%>% 
  select(happiness, marital)%>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=marital, fill=happiness)) + geom_bar(position='fill') + ggtitle("Happiness and Marital Status")

dat%>% 
  select(happiness, marital)%>% 
  group_by(marital)%>%
  count(happiness)

  1. It doesnt seem like political party has much of an effect on happiness and marital status. For all political party identifications, married has the most happy respondents than the rest. Separated still had the least amount of happy respondents. For this I used the variables happiness, partyid, and marital.
ggplot(dat, aes(x=marital, fill=happiness)) + geom_bar() + facet_wrap(~partyid, scales="free_x") + coord_flip() + ggtitle("Happiness, Marital Status, and Political Party") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

  1. My first question is how does the respondents sex affect the happiness and marital status? This question is similar to question 4, but replacing political party with gender. For this I used the variables happiness, sex, and marital.
ggplot(dat, aes(x=marital, fill=happiness)) + geom_bar() + facet_wrap(~sex, scales="free_x") + ggtitle("Happiness, Marital Status, and Sex") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

My second question is how does the respondents age affect their happiness? For this I used the variables happiness and age.

dat%>% 
  select(happiness, age)%>% 
  filter(age > 17)%>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=age, fill=happiness)) + geom_bar(position='fill') + ggtitle("Happiness and Age")
